I've made this recipe twice recently for groups and it was a complete hit - it even won the best recipe award at work for Valentine's Day lunch. It is actually pretty easy to make also - another benefit!

Rating: 3
This was delicious. A couple of changes. I didn't have the fancy moulds, so I just used large heart-shaped cookie cutters. I laid the cheese cloth in there, spooned the mixture in over, folded the extra cheesecloth over, and pressed down to ensure it filled into all the corners evenly. Also -- I melted semi-sweet chocolate, added sweetened condensed milk (can use cream, too.) And used squirt bottles to decorate the plate and heart with raspberry and hot-fudge sauce. Excellent with champagne, followed up with coffee with a dash of chambrod.

Rating: 4
What a perfect, sensuous dessert for Valentine's Day (or any special occasion). It was really easy to make and looked fantastic. However, even though I chilled it in the mold for 24 hrs, it started to melt a bit fairly soon after serving. The raspberry sauce is a must to serve with the coeur.

Rating: 4
This was an incredibly delicious dessert I recently served to my very fussy in-laws following a formal seafood dinner on my husband's birthday. I used a large, free form mold with the cheesecloth and it turned out beautifully! My mother-in-law was actually caught having seconds! The chessecloth is essential--I experimented not using it and things got a bit wet, still delicious, but mushy. If you need to impress the in-laws or the boss, this is a winner!